        <b><span id="titleLabel">W10 - Blueprint for a killer title: how the pros do it</span></b>
        <table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="dateTimeLabel">Tuesday, May 9, 3:30 PM - 5:30 PM</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="roomLabel">Room 404AB</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="descriptionLabel">Four studio heads or company founders will put their game-development and studio-management chops on the line. Before the panel meets, each panelist will have accepted an assignment to create a business plan to bring a game to market. Working with a fixed IP and target platform (mobile, PC, PSP, Xbox 360), they will present and defend a strategy that takes their game from concept, to execution, and into gamers' hands. Topics covered will include the genre best suited for the IP and platform, budget implications, appropriate team organization, target demographic, selection of distribution channel, ROI forecast, and why they believe their game will be a hit. The assignment: your company has secured the rights to create "Lost: The Game," a hypothetical game to be based on the hit TV series. Panel members use real numbers, and standard business practices and terms. No pie-in-the-sky proposals, please. Presentations will be open to scrutiny by the other panelists, who will be invited to interrupt and question the methodology of their co-panelists. Attendees will be given time for questions, so bring your notepads and learn how the industry's most accomplished business executives approach the challenge of delivering their game on time and under budget.</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
